To All:<br>
     Why we lost the war?  The Saigon gov't was a weak dictatorship that the Vietnamese people saw no benefit to support.  America (despite some genuine good intentions among the average soldier) was viewed by the Vietnamese as another foreign power that decided to stick its nose in Vietnam (Many Vietnamese had fought the Japanese and the French).<br>
   From what my father says (he was a Nam vet), I get the impression that the US underestimated the dedication and skill of the enemy.  The NVA/VC were tough soldiers who were dedicated and driven to fight what the perceived as a threat.  American military command didn't use sound judgement in its decision to fight a war of attrition against a ememy willing to take horrible loses and on top of that place restrictions on the air war over the north.<br>
     I guess that I don't understand the miltary effort of leaders that would fight numerous times for the same hill, river or valley.  I give credit to the Vietnamese (north and south) and the American forces (allies included) that could endure a miserable situation like that.  <br>
  
